\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be created.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SM has all three of the necessary ingredients: 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 violating sphaleron processes come from the nonperturbative electroweak
 sector of the SM, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is maximally violated by the chiral fermion couplings of the weak interactions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 is violated by the complex phase in the Cabibbo-Kobayashi-Maskawa (CKM)
 mixing matrix in the quark sector, and the SM plasma could be driven out
 of equilibrium by the electroweak phase transition (EWPT).
 For sufficiently small Higgs mass the EWPT is a first order transition
 which proceeds by bubble formation, analogous to boiling water, a violent
 process that locally departs from thermal equilibrium at the bubble walls.
 It was within the realm of possibility then, before the late 1990s (when
 the LEP2 experiment began placing limits on the Higgs mass), that the SM
 alone could account for baryogenesis.
 However, it is now known that the Higgs mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}=126\ \mathrm{GeV}>72\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $72\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 is the critical point of the EWPT.
 For values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}$
\end_inset

 greater than the critical value the EWPT is a smooth crossover transition
 which does not depart from equilibrium.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}$
\end_inset

 is too large for the EWPT to depart from equilibrium, violating the second
 Sakharov condition.
 Further, detailed computations show that the 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violating phase of the CKM matrix is many orders of magnitude too small
 to account for the observed BAU 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dine2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the time of Sakharov numerous models have been proposed that satisfy
 the Sakharov criteria.
 A recent review counted 44 scenarios in the literature for generating the
 BAU 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shaposhnikov2009"

\end_inset

.
 Of those only a handful are well motivated and provide decent prospects
 for experimental confrontation in the foreseeable future.
 These are the models that propose new particles at or below the electroweak
 scale.
 One prominent option is to include additional scalar fields that couple
 to the SM Higgs and strengthen the EWPT, and may also provide new sources
 of CP violation.
 Such scalars can come from supersymmetric (
\noun on
SUSY
\noun default
) extensions of the SM, such as the well studied MSSM, or from grand unified
 theories (GUTs).
 These models are classified as 
\emph on
electroweak baryogenesis
\emph default
 (
\noun on
EWBG
\noun default
) scenarios since they all involve the EWPT in an extended electroweak/Higgs
 sector.
 Another popular option is 
\emph on
leptogenesis
\emph default
, which posits new fermions which couple to the neutrino sector 
