\begin_layout Standard
When the Higgs develops an expectation value the electroweak symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)_{L}\times U\left(1\right)_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is no longer manifest.
 Instead 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}=\left(W^{1}\mp iW^{2}\right)/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\left(\cos\theta_{W}\right)W^{3}-\left(\sin\theta_{W}\right)B$
\end_inset

 gain mass by the Higgs mechanism, while the orthogonal combination 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\sin\theta_{W}\right)W^{3}+\left(\cos\theta_{W}\right)B$
\end_inset

 becomes the massless photon.
 Expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 I find that the Higgs kinetic term contains a piece
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{Higgs}}\supset\frac{g^{2}v^{2}}{2}W_{\mu}^{+}W^{-\mu}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\cos^{2}\theta_{W}}\frac{g^{2}v^{2}}{2}Z_{\mu}Z^{\mu},
\]

\end_inset

which gives (tree level) masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{W}=gv/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{Z}=m_{W}/\cos\theta_{W}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{W}=g/\sqrt{g^{2}+g'^{2}}$
\end_inset

, and the photon remains massless as claimed.
 The electric charge is identified as 
\begin_inset Formula $e=g\sin\theta_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is modified by radiative corrections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally notice that the SM conserves baryon number 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and lepton number 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 as defined by Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:standard-model-fermions"

\end_inset

.
 These generate a 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
(not gauged) 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)_{B}\times U\left(1\right)_{L}$
\end_inset

 symmetry of the theory.
 This is an accidental symmetry in that it was not put in by design, but
 is rather a result of the fact that the only terms possible to write down
 
\emph on
happen
\emph default
 to obey it.
 It is quite possible that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)_{B}\times U\left(1\right)_{L}$
\end_inset

 is not an exact symmetry of the SM, and indeed quantum effects reduce the
 global symmetry group to 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right)_{B-L}$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the writing down of the SM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just because a classical Lagrangian has a certain symmetry does not mean
 that the full quantum theory will also have that symmetry.
 Indeed, symmetries of theories with chiral fermions coupled to gauge bosons
 are spoiled 
\emph on
chiral anomalies
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Peskin1995,Shaposhnikov1991"

\end_inset

.
 If a classical chiral symmetry is generated by a (in general, reducible)
 representation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{a}$
\end_inset

 acting on all of the fermions in the theory, which is conveniently written
 as a column vector of left chiral fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

, then the anomaly is expressed by the non-conservation of the classical
 current given by
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\lang british
Is this a factor of 2 too big? c.f.
 Shifman 22.8, 34.19
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5a}\equiv\partial_{\mu}\left(\bar{\Psi}\gamma^{\mu}T^{a}\frac{1-\gamma^{5}}{2}\Psi\right)=\sum_{i}-\frac{g_{i}^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}F_{i}^{b\mu\nu}F_{i}^{c\rho\sigma}\mathrm{Tr}\left[T^{a}\left\{ t^{b},t^{c}\right\} \right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 runs over all gauge groups in the theory and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{a}$
\end_inset

 are the generators of the gauge transformations in the (generally reducible)
 representation acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 The trace runs over all of the fermions in the theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is an important consistency condition that the anomalies for all chiral
 currents coupled to gauge bosons vanish.
 Otherwise, unphysical polarisation states of gauge bosons would be created
 and unitarity constraints would be violated in scattering processes.
 If one computes the group theory factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\left[T^{a}\left\{ t^{b},t^{c}\right\} \right]$
\end_inset

 for all the gauge generators of the SM one finds that the theory is indeed
 gauge anomaly free if fermions come in complete generations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The baryon and lepton currents, on the other hand, are anomalous.
 Computing the anomaly coefficients from Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:standard-model-fermions"

\end_inset

 I find
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5B}=\partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5L}=-\frac{n_{g}g^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}W^{a\mu\nu}W^{a\rho\sigma}+\frac{n_{g}g'^{2}}{8\pi^{2}}\epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}B^{\mu\nu}B^{\rho\sigma},\label{eq:B-and-L-anomaly}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, adding and subtracting,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5\left(B-L\right)} & =0,\\
\partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5\left(B+L\right)} & =-\frac{n_{g}g^{2}}{16\pi^{2}}\epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}W^{a\mu\nu}W^{a\rho\sigma}+\frac{n_{g}g'^{2}}{4\pi^{2}}\epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}B^{\mu\nu}B^{\rho\sigma},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{g}=3$
\end_inset

 is the number of fermion generations.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $B+L$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a conserved quantum number of the SM, but 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
is
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate the mechanism of baryon number violation I will simplify the
 SM somewhat.
 It will turn out that the abelian field 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 plays no qualitative role in what follows, so I can take 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{W}\to0$
\end_inset

, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\to0$
\end_inset

, decoupling the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 field from the theory.
 I can also take 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{g}=1$
\end_inset

 and ignore the Higgs-Yukawa couplings of the fermions as these play no
 qualitative role.
 The mechanism of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 violation is topological in nature, invisible to perturbation theory.
 At zero temperature it proceeds by quantum tunnelling between gauge vacua
 with different topologies.
 A potential barrier separates these field configurations and the leading
 contribution to the transition rate at zero temperature comes from the
 semi-classical tunnelling trajectory called an 
\emph on
instanton
\emph default
, discovered by 't Hooft and Polyakov.
 Later, Kuzmin, Rubakov and Shaposhnikov argued that at finite temperature
 the transition proceeds by classical fluctuations 
\emph on
over the barrier
\emph default
 at a rate increasing exponentially with temperature, finally becoming unsuppres
sed entirely at sufficiently high temperature.
 The height of the barrier can be computed by finding the (unstable) configurati
on of the gauge and Higgs fields that maximises the energy atop the barrier.
 These configurations are called 
\emph on
sphalerons
\emph default
 and were discovered by Klinkhamer and Manton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klinkhamer1984"

\end_inset

.
 Further early analysis of these configurations in the SM were carried out
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arnold1987,Arnold1988"

\end_inset

.
 Pedagogical discussions can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shaposhnikov1991,Shifman2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The topological nature of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 violating transitions can be seen by integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:B-and-L-anomaly"

\end_inset

 and examining what gauge field configurations can give a non-zero contribution
 to the right hand side:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta B=\Delta L & =\int\mathrm{d}^{4}x\ \partial_{\mu}j^{\mu5\left(B,L\right)}\\
 & =-\frac{g^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{4}x\ \epsilon_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}W^{a\mu\nu}W^{a\rho\sigma}\\
 & =\frac{g^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{4}x\ \partial_{\mu}K^{\mu},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\lang british
Factor of 2 here? c.f.
 Shifman eq.
 18.12 (also note 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to-g$
\end_inset

 there c.f.
 eq.
 18.2); Update 25/11/2013 this seems to work with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=n_{w}$
\end_inset

, haven't yet checked with the anomaly eq.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K^{\mu}=4\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}\left(W_{\nu}^{a}\partial_{\alpha}W_{\beta}^{a}-\frac{g}{3}\epsilon^{abc}W_{\nu}^{a}W_{\alpha}^{b}W_{\beta}^{c}\right),
\]

\end_inset

is the 
\emph on
Chern-Simons
\emph default
 current.
 The 
\emph on
Chern-Simons number
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the charge corresponding to this current:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{K}=\frac{g^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ K^{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=\Delta L=\Delta\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 only Chern-Simons number changing transitions contribute to baryon and
 lepton number violation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider for the moment vacuum field configurations.
 In this case the gauge fields must be pure gauge: 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mu}=\frac{i}{g}U^{\dagger}\partial_{\mu}U$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\in SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 All of these states have zero energy.
 Choose the static gauge 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 for simplicity, implying 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\vec{x},t\right)=U\left(\vec{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The vacuum configurations must be connectible by trajectories with finite
 action (any states separated by an infinite action are physically inaccessible,
 even by quantum tunnelling.) This sets the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to\text{const.}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{x}\right|\to\infty$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 going to any constant matrix is acceptable, and all choices are physically
 equivalent).
 This boundary condition is the same as compactifying the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 by adding a point at infinity, resulting in a space topologically equivalent
 (homeomorphic) to the three-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 But the group 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is also homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be seen by writing a general matrix in 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a+id & b+ic\\
-b+ic & a-id
\end{array}\right)\in SU\left(2\right),
\]

\end_inset

for real 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d$
\end_inset

 and noting that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(U\right)=1$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}+d^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This defines a three-sphere of unit radius.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $U:\left(\mathbb{R}^{3}\cup\infty\right)\to SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is a mapping of three-spheres 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}\to S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These mappings fall into topologically distinct classes classified by the
 third homotopy group of the three-sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{3}\left(S^{3}\right)=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{w}\in\pi_{3}\left(S^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 associated in this way to a mapping is called 
\emph on
winding number
\emph default
 and counts the number of times the map 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 winds around the group 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Both real space and the group space are oriented so it makes sense to talk
 about negative winding numbers.
 Maps with the same winding number can be continuously deformed to each
 other by a 
\emph on
small gauge transformation
\emph default
, while 
\emph on
large gauge transformations
\emph default
 change the winding number by an integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Chern-Simons number of the vacuum configurations can be evaluated as
 follows.
 First rewrite the Chern-Simons current in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
K^{\mu} & =4\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}W_{\nu}^{a}\partial_{\alpha}W_{\beta}^{a}-4\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}\frac{g}{3}\epsilon^{abc}W_{\nu}^{a}W_{\alpha}^{b}W_{\beta}^{c}\\
 & =2\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}W_{\nu}^{a}W_{\alpha\beta}^{a}+\frac{2}{3}g\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}\epsilon^{abc}W_{\nu}^{a}W_{\alpha}^{b}W_{\beta}^{c}\\
 & =-\frac{16}{3g^{2}}i\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}\epsilon^{abc}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}U\tau^{b}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\tau^{c}\right)\\
 & =-\frac{8}{3g^{2}}\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish the last equality a useful identity is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\epsilon^{abc}\mathrm{Tr}\left(A\tau^{a}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(B\tau^{b}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(C\tau^{c}\right) & =-\frac{1}{4}i\mathrm{Tr}\left(A\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(B\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(C\right)+\frac{1}{4}i\mathrm{Tr}\left(A\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(BC\right)\\
 & +\frac{1}{4}i\mathrm{Tr}\left(B\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(AC\right)+\frac{1}{4}i\mathrm{Tr}\left(C\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(AB\right)\\
 & -\frac{1}{2}i\mathrm{Tr}\left(ABC\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C\in SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

, which can be proven using the further useful identities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\left(\tau^{a}\tau^{b}\tau^{c}\right)=\frac{i}{4}\epsilon^{abc}$
\end_inset

 and the Fierz identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ij}^{a}\tau_{kl}^{a}=-\frac{1}{4}\delta_{ij}\delta_{kl}+\frac{1}{2}\delta_{ik}\delta_{jl}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying this with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U$
\end_inset

 etc.
 and noting that the antisymmetry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon^{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 kills all but the last term gives the desired result.
 Finally evaluate the Chern-Simons number
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{K} & =\frac{g^{2}}{32\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ K^{0}\\
 & =-\frac{1}{12\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ \epsilon^{0\nu\alpha\beta}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ \frac{1}{6}\epsilon^{\nu\alpha\beta}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ \frac{\partial^{3}\Omega}{\partial^{3}x},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where used 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon^{0\nu\alpha\beta}=\epsilon^{\nu\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,\alpha,\beta=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{3}\Omega}{\partial^{3}x}\equiv\frac{1}{6}\epsilon^{\nu\alpha\beta}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}UU^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\right),
\]

\end_inset

is the natural 
\emph on
oriented
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 invariant group volume element (the 
\emph on
Haar measure
\emph default
).
 The integral then measures the oriented volume swept out in the group as
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 varies over all space; and since the volume of the group is the volume
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 counts the number of times the full group is swept out as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 varies over all space.
 Thus I find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=n_{w}$
\end_inset

, the Chern-Simons number is just the winding number of the gauge field
 configuration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A gauge vacuum with nontrivial winding can be found by choosing
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\exp\left(-i\tau^{a}\frac{x^{a}}{r}f\left(r\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

and noting the boundary conditions demand that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(0\right)=2\pi n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\infty\right)=2\pi m$
\end_inset

 for integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m$
\end_inset

.
 I illustrate the calculation of the Chern-Simons number of this configuration
 because it is hard to find in the literature and it is only straightforward
 once one knows where to start.
 It is easiest to use the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{0}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 rather than the form involving the group volume element.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
K^{0} & \propto\epsilon^{0\nu\alpha\beta}\epsilon^{abc}\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\alpha}U\tau^{b}\right)\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\beta}U\tau^{c}\right)\\
 & =6\det\left[\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thinking of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,a$
\end_inset

 indices.
 After a bit of algebra I find
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)=-i\frac{1}{2}\frac{x^{a}}{r}\partial_{\nu}f-i\partial_{\nu}\left(\frac{x^{a}}{r}\right)\sin\left(\frac{f}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{f}{2}\right)+i\epsilon^{abc}\frac{x^{b}}{r}\partial_{\nu}\left(\frac{x^{c}}{r}\right)\sin^{2}\left(\frac{f}{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left[\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)\right]=\frac{i}{4r^{2}}\left(1-\cos f\right)f',
\]

\end_inset

leading to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{K} & =-\frac{i}{2\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\det\left[\mathrm{Tr}\left(U^{\dagger}\partial_{\nu}U\tau^{a}\right)\right]\\
 & =-\frac{i}{2\pi^{2}}\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\frac{if'\left(1-\cos f\right)}{4r^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}r\ f'\left(1-\cos f\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\left[f-\sin f\right]_{0}^{\infty}\\
 & =m-n.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the basic winding configuration has 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that only the boundary values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 enter into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

, confirming the topological nature of the Chern-Simons number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bringing the argument together: there is an infinitude of gauge vacua characteri
sed by the topological invariant 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 If there is a transition from one gauge vacuum to another which changes
 the winding number by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta n_{w}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=\Delta L=\Delta\mathcal{K}=\Delta n_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=\Delta L=n_{g}\Delta\mathcal{K}=n_{g}\Delta n_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}=n_{w}$
\end_inset

 only holds for vacuum states.
 For excited states 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 varies continuous and is not necessarily an integer.
 Thus I can sketch the potential energy along the 
