\begin_layout Standard
In this report I have discussed the essential physics behind electroweak
 baryogenesis scenarios and given two examples of nonequilibrium quantum
 field theory techniques applied to simple scalar/fermion theories.
 It was not possible to explore these topics in any great depth in this
 report.
 Indeed the research literature on baryogenesis and nonequilibrium QFT has
 thousands of papers.
 The work presented here is admittedly a somewhat eclectic mix of topics
 taken from these fields, and the connections between them may not be obvious.
 Here I draw out the main lessons learned in this investigation, highlight
 current outstanding problems and potential directions for future work and
 their significance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The obvious major problem facing EWBG scenarios is the order of the electroweak
 phase transition.
 It is necessary for the transition to proceed through bubble formation
 as in a first order transition, and also that the scalar field behind the
 bubble wall be sufficiently large (a measure of the strength of the phase
 transition) that sphaleron processes are effectively shut off, lest they
 erase the baryon asymmetry that was so painstakingly created.
 We have already seen that lattice methods are required for the EWPT in
 the SM with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{h}=125\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 and that these studies indicates that there is only a smooth crossover
 transition.
 In this case there is no bubble nucleation and the plasma never departs
 far enough from equilibrium to satisfy the Sakharov criteria.
 Thus it is necessary to extend the SM to obtain EWBG.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most straightforward approach to strengthening the EWPT is adding new
 scalar fields which are strongly coupled to the Higgs.
 In the MSSM the stops (top quark superpartners), particularly the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{t}_{R}$
\end_inset

, and the second Higgs doublet are suitable candidates, although current
 LHC data favours a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

split
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mini-split
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scenario where the stops are relatively heavy compared to the weak scale
 and hence decouple from the EWPT-relevant physics (a discussion of the
 most current constraints on natural SUSY can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Evans2013"

\end_inset

).
 Thus the standard view in the recent literature is that EWBG in the MSSM
 is nearly ruled out (see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chung2013"

\end_inset

 for a discussion in the MSSM and more generally); however, recent lattice
 Monte Carlo studies using dimensional reduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kajantie1996,Laine2012,Laine2013"

\end_inset

 suggest that the EWPT in the light stop scenario is much stronger than
 the perturbative estimates previously employed, and the tension with LHC
 data is further reduced if the 
\begin_inset Formula $125\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 Higgs can decay into 
\begin_inset Formula $m\lesssim60\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 neutralinos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Carena2012"

\end_inset

.
 Thus to the author's knowledge EWBG within the MSSM remains worthy of considera
tion, at least until the end of run 2 of the LHC.
 The addition of a single gauge singlet chiral superfield, giving the NMSSM,
 alleviates the constraints considerably 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Balazs2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-supersymmetric extensions are possible as well, the most popular being
 the two Higgs doublet models (
\noun on
2HDM
\noun default
).
 Though having two Higgs doublets like the MSSM, these models can differ
 significantly from the MSSM in terms of phenomenology because of the absence
 of coloured scalars and the relaxation of SUSY constraints on the scalar
 potential (i.e., the 2HDM potential does not have to be derivable from a
 holomorphic superpotential).
 This extra freedom carries the danger of generating large flavour changing
 neutral currents (
\noun on
FCNC
\noun default
) which are strongly constrained.
 This problem is bypassed by imposing a discrete symmetry on the theory
 to restrict the Yukawa couplings, resulting in four discrete classes of
 2HDM corresponding to the possible charge assignments under the discrete
 symmetry
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The SUSY pattern of Higgs couplings corresponds to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Type II
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 2HDM.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This discrete choice has no impact on the EWPT or indeed the goodness-of-fit
 of the best fit models (which is insignificantly better than the SM at
 this stage), but does impact the experimental constraints on the parameter
 space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cheung2013"

\end_inset

.
 A recent scan of the parameter space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dorsch2013"

\end_inset

 finds large regions which are compatible with all LHC constraints and which
 have strong first order phase transitions (at the one loop, daisy resummed
 level) and it was argued that these models are generically favourable towards
 EWBG.
 However, only a rough estimate of the wall velocities was performed, based
 on the hydrodynamical model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huber2013"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violation generation and washout were not addressed in any detail.
 2HDM remains a promising class of models for EWBG and worthy of further
 investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to investigate new physics in a fairly model independent
 way.
 If the new physics, however complicated, exists at a scale 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which is heaver than the weak scale 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, and there exists a separation scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v\ll\Lambda\lesssim M$
\end_inset

 then it is possible to use an effective field theory below the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 with only the SM degrees of freedom.
 The new physics manifests as additional operators in the Lagrangian:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{SM}}+\sum_{i}\frac{1}{\Lambda}c_{i}^{\left(5\right)}\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5\right)}+\sum_{i}\frac{1}{\Lambda^{2}}c_{i}^{\left(3\right)}\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(6\right)}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\Lambda^{3}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 are the set of all gauge invariant operators of mass dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 respectively built only out of SM fields
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do not confuse the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 with the mathematical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

big-oh
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 are dimensionless (
\emph on
Wilson
\emph default
) coefficients which are expected to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 if they come from a generic model of new physics (if the new physics has
 a symmetry some of the coefficients can vanish, or be loop suppressed).
 Amplitudes calculated in the effective theory are expected to be accurate
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E/\Lambda\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

 corrections, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is energy scale for the process at hand.
 The Wilson coefficients are typically obtained by matching correlation
 functions in the effective field theory to those calculated in the full
 theory to the given order of accuracy.
 It is possible to remove from the set of operators those which vanish by
 the SM equations of motion and those which are linearly dependent.
 Note that linear independence is not always trivial to check due to the
 possible use Fierz rearrangement identities, integration by parts and equations
 of motion.
 A complete basis of linearly independent operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 has been found for the SM degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grzadkowski2010"

\end_inset

.
 Altogether there are 65 of them: one dimension 5 term that generates Majorana
 neutrino masses after electroweak symmetry breaking, and 64 dimension 6
 operators: 59 of which conserve 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, and 5 four-fermion contact interactions which violate
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that such operators are typically constrained to a very high scale
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\gtrsim10^{12}\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 as they generate tree-level proton decay, unlike the non-perturbative sphaleron
/instanton processes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (but conserve 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L$
\end_inset

).
 Of all of these operators, only one affects the Higgs potential: the dimension
 six term 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a conservative, and largely model independent, exploration of BSM
 modifications to the Higgs potential can be achieved by taking as the Higgs
 potential
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\Phi\right)=\mu^{2}\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi+\frac{\lambda^{2}}{2}\left(\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{\Lambda^{2}}\left(\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi\right)^{3}.
\]

\end_inset

EWBG with this potential has been investigated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grojean2005"

\end_inset

 which finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\sim500-800\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 gives a strong first order phase transition for the physical Higgs mass
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{h}=125\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

 term is very difficult to probe at the LHC, thus the constraints are weak
 unless the new physics generates other dimension 6 operators at the same
 scale.
 As a result, LHC constraints do not yet significantly touch this range
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, though with enough luminosity at 
\begin_inset Formula $14\ \mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

 the LHC could begin to constrain this scenario through measurements of
 the Higgs cubic self-coupling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grojean2005,Chung2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary we have seen that it is easy to strengthen the EWPT in BSM models
 of current phenomenological interest.
 This strongly motivates the experimental search for exotic Higgs decays
 and non-SM particles in the scalar sector.
 An extensive review of the experimental prospects for these searches, including
 all LHC data to date, can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Curtin2013"

\end_inset

.
 However, questions can be raised about the computation of the phase transition
 thermodynamics.
 A conceptual question of great practical import is the gauge dependence
 of this theory, which is relevant in the Higgs theory because an expectation
 value of a gauge-variant quantity like 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is physically meaningless.
 Two methods are available to check the gauge dependence of the result:
 redo the computation in a general class of gauges such as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\xi}$
\end_inset

 gauge and check the dependence on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 parameter, or develop a formulation using only manifestly gauge invariant
 quantities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi$
\end_inset

.
 An example of the first method is the jump of the order parameter at the
 critical temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}/T_{c}$
\end_inset

, calculated by standard techniques in the SM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Patel2011"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\phi_{c}}{T_{c}}=\frac{3-\xi^{3/2}}{48\pi\lambda}\left(2g_{2}^{3}+\left(g_{1}^{2}+g_{2}^{2}\right)^{3/2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Higgs quartic coupling and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(1\right),SU\left(2\right)_{L}$
\end_inset

 gauge couplings respectively (note the normalisation convention for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is different from ours!).
 Note the spurious gauge dependence of this quantity.
 Indeed by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=3^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 the order parameter can be made to vanish! Similarly, calculations of the
 sphaleron rate and washout factors are gauge dependent and so far only
 lattice results are theoretically solid, but these have only been done
 in a small number of cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrissey2012"

\end_inset

.
 As a result it is difficult to say whether a given phase transition is
 indeed strong enough to avoid washing out a baryon asymmetry.
 The vast majority of treatments ignore these issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of the second method is the lattice Monte Carlo method, where
 it is necessary to use gauge invariant order parameters from the outset
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moore1997,Bodeker1999"

\end_inset

 for examples showing how gauge invariant observables can be judiciously
 chosen to extract the desired physics).
 Unfortunately it is infeasible to implement and interpret lattice computations
 for every scenario in every model of interest, so it remains valuable to
 develop appropriately gauge invariant perturbative methods.
 Also, lattice methods can only be straightforwardly applied to equilibrium
 problems.
 Thus real time methods which allow an extension to non-equilibrium situations
 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 have manifestly good gauge invariance properties are particularly valuable.
 The chief difficultly with the development of perturbative methods for
 the phase transition is the infrared divergences associated with the Higgs
 and gauge bosons near the critical point.
 Physically, soft modes of these fields become highly occupied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A promising approach is an effective theory where the soft modes are treated
 classically, while the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 modes with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\gtrsim gT$
\end_inset

 are treated quantum mechanically.
 The dynamics of the back-reaction of the fluctuating hard modes on the
 soft modes is captured by an effective noise kernel and one obtains a Langevin
 equation for the soft modes.
 This theory was developed for pure 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 gauge theory by B
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
"{o}
\end_layout

\end_inset

deker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bodeker1998"

\end_inset

 and was originally intended for lattice computations, however a perturbative
 reformulation using ideas from stochastic quantisation was the topic of
 recent Ph.D work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zahlten2004"

\end_inset

 and extensions of this work represent an intriguing possibility.
 Other promising new directions are the new perturbation theory of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Millington2012,Millington2013"

\end_inset

 which reorganises the perturbation theory using non-homogeneous propagators
 and vertices to remove 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pinch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 singularities associated with thermally occupied modes, the symmetry improved
 
\noun on
CJT
\noun default
 formalism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pilaftsis2013,Mao2013"

\end_inset

 which enforces Ward identities by the use of Lagrange multipliers so that
 truncations of the Schwinger-Dyson hierarchy are manifestly invariant (so
 far only applied to scalar field theories, not gauge theories), and the
 development of non-perturbative renormalisation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Garny2008"

\end_inset

 (so far for scalar fields only) and gauge invariant non-equilibrium 2PI
 techniques 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zoller2013"

\end_inset

 for abelian gauge theories.
 Clearly a recent trend is the reorganisation of perturbation theory, using
 self-consistent schemes much like those explored in this report, to gain
 access to hitherto inaccessible regimes of quantum field theories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once a first order phase transition is in hand, the probability of bubble
 formation can be found in equilibrium by saddle-point evaluation of the
 Euclidean functional integral.
 At zero temperature the pioneering theory of Coleman and Callan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coleman1977,Callan1977a"

\end_inset

 remains essentially unmodified (c.f.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Linde1990,Dine1992,Shifman2012"

\end_inset

 for more recent, though notably unoriginal with respect to this theory,
 discussions).
 They find that the bubble formation probability per unit volume per unit
 time for a single scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and false vacuum solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{+}$
\end_inset

 (with the convention 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\phi_{+}\right)=0$
\end_inset

) is to leading semi-classical order
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\Gamma}{V} & =\mathrm{e}^{-B/\hbar}\frac{B^{2}}{4\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}\left|\frac{\det'\left[-\partial^{2}+U''\left(\bar{\phi}\right)\right]}{\det\left[-\partial^{2}+U''\left(\phi_{+}\right)\right]}\right|^{-\frac{1}{2}}\\
 & \times\left[1+\mathcal{O}\left(\hbar\right)\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
bounce action
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\int\mathrm{d}^{4}x_{E}\ \frac{1}{2}\left(\partial\bar{\phi}\right)^{2}+U\left(\bar{\phi}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\emph default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is the solution of the Euclidean (imaginary time) equations of motion with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x_{E}\to\infty\right)=\phi_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 The prime on 
\begin_inset Formula $\det'$
\end_inset

 indicates that the zero modes of the differential operator are excluded
 from the functional determinant.
 The functional integrals over the zero modes correspond to integrating
 over all possible bubble centres and nucleation times, which is accounted
 for by the 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{2}/4\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}$
\end_inset

 prefactor.
 Extension of the theory to finite temperatures is in principle straightforward:
 one looks for solutions which are periodic in imaginary time with period
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar/k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
 At high temperatures the problem is effectively reduced to a three dimensional
 one and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\to\frac{\hbar}{k_{B}T}S_{3}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 is the three dimensional action 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dine1992,Linde1990"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally the evaluation of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a tractable numerical problem, though analytical results are available
 for the very widely used 
\emph on
thin wall approximation
\emph default
, but the evaluation of the functional determinants ranges from very difficult
 to hopeless.
 Thus one typically guesses the prefactor based on scaling and dimensional
 analysis and attempts to validate this guess by comparison to lattice Monte
 Carlo simulations.
 So far this program has only been carried out for a small number of benchmark
 models.
 In cases of phenomenological interest for EWBG where multiple scalar fields
 are participating in the phase transition the nucleation rate is in principle
 a straightforward extension of these standard results, but the computational
 difficulty increases with the complexity of the scalar sector.
 Often one finds thin wall results applied without the validity of the approxima
tion being checked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another point worth noting is that there is no real time description of
 bubble nucleation.
 The situation is analogous to a particle tunnelling through a barrier in
 a quantum mechanical system: one does not ask about the time evolution
 of the particle while the particle is under the barrier.
 Instead one finds that the wavefunction leaks through the barrier; the
 particle itself presumably makes some kind of quantum leap.
 Similarly a real time description of bubble nucleation must involve the
 wave-functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\left[\phi\right]$
\end_inset

 (or density matrix functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\rho}\left[\phi_{1},\phi_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

) which is initially, say, a Gaussian centred on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{+}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\sim\exp\left[-\int\mathrm{d}^{3}x\ \frac{\mu}{2}\left(\phi-\phi_{+}\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 but which gradually develops a component on the other side of the barrier.
 It is not clear what, if anything, such a description would yield of practical
 relevance.
 In particular, decoherence between branches of the wave-functional with
 different histories of bubble nucleation is probably large, but the author
 knows of no discussion of this topic in the literature.
 A more important practical question is the gauge dependence of the formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After critical bubbles nucleate they expand.
 Since the scalar fields involved are large it is expected that the evolution
 of the bubble is classical from this point on, and indeed this approximation
 is universally made in the literature.
 In principle one should check to what degree the state resulting from the
 nucleation process is in fact a coherent state, and allow for the possibilities
 of quantum particle creation and charge fractionalisation on the bubble
 wall 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shifman2012"

\end_inset

, though such effects are almost certainly small once the bubble reaches
 a macroscopic size.
 The classical theory of macroscopic bubble expansion is well developed
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Espinosa2010,Huber2013"

\end_inset

.
 It is assumed that not only is the Higgs field in a coherent state, but
 that the plasma is well described by quasi-particles with near equilibrium
 distribution functions (in the rest frame of the plasma) 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=\left\{ \exp\left[\gamma\left(E-vp_{z}\right)/T\right]\pm1\right\} ^{-1}+\delta f_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta f_{i}\ll f_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1/\sqrt{1-v^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the plasma velocity in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction which is taken to be perpendicular to the wall.
 The equation of motion for the mean value of the Higgs field is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\square\phi+\frac{\partial F}{\partial\phi}+\sum_{i}\frac{\mathrm{d}m_{i}^{2}}{\mathrm{d}\phi}\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}p}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}2E_{i}}\delta f_{i}\left(p\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the finite temperature effective potential for the Higgs and the third
 term is the friction term, which is due to the deviation of the particle
 distribution functions from equilibrium.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta f_{i}$
\end_inset

 are found by solving a network of Boltzmann equations for the particle
 transport in the vicinity of the bubble wall.
 This program is very difficult (and questions about the applicability of
 Boltzmann equations remain), and has only been carried out in any detail
 in the SM and MSSM.
 In other models one computes a simple phenomenological friction coefficient
 and then calibrates it relative to the SM value which has been computed
 much more accurately.
 Once the phenomenological friction coefficient is obtained the bubble expansion
 is a hydrodynamic problem which has essentially been solved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Boltzmann equations can be derived from first principles quantum transport
 equations (Kadanoff-Baym equations) under the assumption of weak gradients
 and the lack of memory effects or coherence.
 Coherence can arise, for example, as a result of flavour oscillations,
 in which case the treatment must be extended from single particle distribution
 functions to two particle density matrices.
 Recent advances have applied quantum transport techniques to those species
 involved in the creation of CP violation and baryon number, with the finding
 that resonant flavour oscillations can lead to an enhancement of the asymmetry
 produced, however the bulk plasma properties are still treated semi-classically
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baryon production is largely dependent on the production of CP violation
 in fermion scattering off bubble walls and the diffusion of the asymmetric
 species into the plasma ahead of the bubble wall, which must be subsonic
 for such diffusion to happen
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Though see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caprini2011"

\end_inset

 for an alternate EWBG mechanism involving supersonic bubble walls.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The faster an asymmetric species diffuses, the longer it remains ahead
 of the bubble wall, and the longer sphalerons have to convert it into a
 net baryon asymmetry.
 Thus a solid understanding of the scattering and transport of plasma particles
 in the bubble region is essential to a reliable EWBG calculation.
 Recent progress has achieved this, up to some small open questions, in
 the context of the MSSM (for a review see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

).
 Open questions regard the validity of some of the approximations used in
 deriving Boltzmann equations, then continuity equations, from the Kadanoff-Baym
 equations.
 In particular these are the gradient expansion - usually truncated to lowest
 non-trivial order, the quasiparticle approximation (the applicability of
 distribution functions), the fluid approximation (distribution functions
 have the equilibrium form with spacetime varying velocity, temperature
 and chemical potential) and weak coupling.
 Also reactions which are very fast compared to the diffusion time are treated
 by constraining the chemical potentials of the species involved, while
 those very slow compared to the diffusion time are ignored.
 Only those reactions which take place on a similar time scale to the diffusion
 time require detailed treatment.
 These techniques have not yet seen wide application to BSM models other
 than the MSSM, although the SM with the dimension six term 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

, a scalar singlet SM extension, 2HDM (Types I and II), MSSM, and NMSSM
 are each briefly discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

.
 The general finding is that apart from the MSSM, the main portion of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 asymmetry generated in each model is due to a semi-classical force term
 and that the possibility of resonant enhancement, the topic of much recent
 debate, is unimportant.
 The Kadanoff-Baym framework is a solid foundation, thus I view the problem
 of fermion transport in EWBG as a problem where incremental model-dependent
 progress is an important possibility, but no major advances should be expected.
\end_layout

