\begin_layout Standard
The basic idea of the method is quite simple.
 Consider a quantum system in some initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi_{0}}$
\end_inset

 at an initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 of some operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O\left(t\right)=\Braket{\Psi\left(t\right)|\hat{O}\left(t\right)|\Psi\left(t\right)}=\Braket{\Psi_{0}|\hat{U}\left(t_{0},t\right)\hat{O}\left(t\right)\hat{U}\left(t,t_{0}\right)|\Psi_{0}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\left(t,t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the time evolution operator.
 As usual 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\left(t_{2},t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}>t_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in terms of a time ordered exponential
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{U}\left(t_{2},t_{1}\right)=\mathrm{T}\left\{ \exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}\mathrm{d}\tau\ \hat{H}\left(\tau\right)\right)\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

but, for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}<t_{1}$
\end_inset

, an 
\emph on
anti-time ordered
\emph default
 exponential is required:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{U}\left(t_{2},t_{1}\right)=\tilde{\mathrm{T}}\left\{ \exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}\mathrm{d}\tau\ \hat{H}\left(\tau\right)\right)\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

 orders operators in the opposite sense to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 earlier times to the left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting these in the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O\left(t\right)=\Braket{\Psi_{0}|\tilde{\mathrm{T}}\left\{ \exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{t}^{t_{0}}\mathrm{d}\tau\ \hat{H}\left(\tau\right)\right)\right\} \hat{O}\left(t\right)\mathrm{T}\left\{ \exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\mathrm{d}\tau\ \hat{H}\left(\tau\right)\right)\right\} |\Psi_{0}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be simplified by interpreting the time evolution as along a 
\emph on
two branched
\emph default
 contour 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 which runs from 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 then doubles back to 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Introducing a contour time variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 as an affine parameter on the contour
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An explicit mapping of 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left(t_{0},2t-t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 to ordinary time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\left(t_{0},t\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=z$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}\leq z\leq t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2t-z$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t<z<2t-t_{0}$
\end_inset

, but this is rarely needed in practice.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and a 
\emph on
contour time ordering
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O\left(t\right)=\Braket{\Psi_{0}|\mathrm{T}_{C}\left\{ \exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z\ \hat{H}\left(z\right)\right)\hat{O}\left(t\right)\right\} |\Psi_{0}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Further, both branches of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 can be extended to an arbitrary time 
\begin_inset Formula $T>t$
\end_inset

, removing the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 dependence of the contour.
 Since there are no operators in the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,T\right)$
\end_inset

 the segment of the evolution from 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and back is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}\left(t,T\right)\hat{U}\left(T,t\right)=\hat{\mathbb{I}}$
\end_inset

 and cancels outs, so no modification of the above expression is necessary.
 There is an ambiguity where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 should go on the contour, i.e.
 how to generalise 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}\left(t\right)\to\hat{O}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

, but for convenience 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 can be taken to be the same operator on both branches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generalisation of this result to multiple operators and a general initial
 density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}_{0}=\sum_{n}p_{n}\ket n\bra n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the system is in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket n$
\end_inset

, is obvious:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle O_{1}\left(z_{1}\right)O_{2}\left(z_{2}\right)\cdots\right\rangle =\mathrm{Tr}\left\{ \hat{\rho}_{0}\mathrm{T}_{C}\left[\exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z\ \hat{H}\left(z\right)\right)\hat{O}_{1}\left(z_{1}\right)\hat{O}_{2}\left(z_{2}\right)\cdots\right]\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Proceeding still further, a general density matrix can be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\rho}_{0}=Z^{-1}\exp\left(-\beta\hat{H}_{M}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 Hermitian operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is chosen to ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}\hat{\rho}_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 (in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 can be absorbed into a shift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

 if so desired).
 If the Hamiltonian of the system is time independent and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}=\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 then this describes a thermal equilibrium state at temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 However, there is no loss of generality in writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}_{0}$
\end_inset

 in this way with a general 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

, and out of equilibrium the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is entirely arbitrary, equivalent to an arbitrary normalisation convention
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Now note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-\beta\hat{H}_{M}\right)=\exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{0}-i\beta\hbar}\mathrm{d}\tau\ \hat{H}_{M}\right)=\hat{U}\left(t_{0}-i\beta\hbar,t_{0};\hat{H}_{M}\right)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 up to an overall normalisation factor the initial density matrix can be
 written as the time evolution operator for an 
\emph on
imaginary
\emph default
 time interval with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

 (assuming a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-independent 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

).
 Extending the contour 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 with a segment on the imaginary axis from 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}-i\beta\hbar$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
defining
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}\left(z\right)=\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 on this segment then, taking care with the normalisation,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \mathrm{T}_{C}\left[O_{1}\left(z_{1}\right)O_{2}\left(z_{2}\right)\cdots\right]\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\mathrm{Tr}\left\{ \mathrm{T}_{C}\left[\exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z\ \hat{H}\left(z\right)\right)\hat{O}_{1}\left(z_{1}\right)\hat{O}_{2}\left(z_{2}\right)\cdots\right]\right\} }{\mathrm{Tr}\left\{ \mathrm{T}_{C}\left[\exp\left(-\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z\ \hat{H}\left(z\right)\right)\right]\right\} }\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathcal{L}\right)\hat{O}_{1}\left(z_{1}\right)\hat{O}_{2}\left(z_{2}\right)\cdots}{\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{C}\mathcal{L}\right)},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the second line specialises to field theory and extends the path integral
 and Lagrangian to all branches of the contour.
 The imaginary branch of the contour is called the 
\emph on
Matsubara
\emph default
 branch, as this is the same contour used in the imaginary time field theory
 formalism for thermal equilibrium problems.
 The similarity of this result to the usual vacuum field theory formula
 should be obvious, however 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 assumptions have been made about the initial/final state or spectrum of
 the theory.
 This greatly extends the applicability of the formalism compared to the
 usual vacuum field theory.
 Despite this, much of the technical machinery of the vacuum theory, including
 path integrals, Feynman diagrams, effective actions and renormalisation,
 can be carried over with suitable modifications for contour time ordering
 as opposed to regular time ordering.
 Difficulties come from the extra degrees of freedom (fields on the backward
 branch of the contour), the explicit appearance of memory effects, and
 choosing a 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{M}$
\end_inset

 that allows for consistent and practically solvable renormalisation conditions.
\end_layout

