\begin_layout Standard
The origin of some of the names can be seen by visualising the function
 arguments on the time contour.
 For example, the lesser function is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta^{<}\left(x,y\right)=-i\left\langle \hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\hat{\phi}\left(x\right)\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

i.e.
 the second argument appears to the left of the first in the matrix element,
 regardless of the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 So the lesser function orders the fields 
\emph on
as if 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}<y^{0}$
\end_inset

, even if it is not.
 The hook functions are similarly visual.
 Consider the left hook function 
\begin_inset Formula $\lhook\Delta\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

: the left argument is on the Matsubara (vertical) branch and the right
 argument is on a real time (horizontal) branch (it does not matter which
 one since the contour ordering is the same in both cases).
 The contour delta function is defined so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z'\ \delta_{C}\left(z,z'\right)f\left(z'\right)=f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 as usual.
 The only nontrivial reduction to an ordinary delta function is when (taking
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 for simplicity) 
\begin_inset Formula $z=-i\tau$
\end_inset

 lies on the Matsubara branch:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{C}\mathrm{d}z'\ \delta_{C}\left(-i\tau,z'\right)f\left(z'\right)=f\left(-i\tau\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The only contribution can come from 
\begin_inset Formula $z'$
\end_inset

 on the Matsubara branch, so substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $z'=-i\tau'$
\end_inset

 giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{-i\beta\hbar}\mathrm{d}\left(-i\tau'\right)\delta_{C}\left(-i\tau,-i\tau'\right)f\left(-i\tau'\right)=f\left(-i\tau\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{C}\left(-i\tau,-i\tau'\right)=i\delta\left(\tau-\tau'\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When working with the Keldysh components it is convenient to have identities
 for the reduction of frequently occuring convolutions and products of contour
 time functions to their components.
 These identities are called 
\emph on
Langreth rules
\emph default
 and are summarised in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Langreth-rules"

\end_inset

.
 These identities are proved in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stefanucci2013"

\end_inset

 chapter 5.
 The most common use of these identities is in the reduction of equations
 of motion for contour ordered Green functions to equations for real times
 functions.
 For example, if a scalar field Green function obeys a Dyson equation of
 the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square_{x}\Delta\left(x,y\right)=i\delta_{C}\left(x,y\right)+\int_{z}\Sigma\left(x,z\right)\Delta\left(z,y\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\square_{x}=\partial_{\mu}^{\left(x\right)}\partial^{\left(x\right)\mu}$
\end_inset

 and the self energy function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is also defined on the time contour, the Langreth rules show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{<}$
\end_inset

 obeys (suppressing arguments)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square_{x}\Delta^{<}=\Sigma^{<}\cdot\Delta^{A}+\Sigma^{R}\cdot\Delta^{<}+\rhook\Sigma\star\lhook\Delta,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

an equation suitable for numerical solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Green functions contain the physical information of the theory.
 This can be seen explicitly in the simplifying case of free fields where
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=0$
\end_inset

 and the Dyson equation can be solved simply by Fourier transform.
 Writing
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta^{\left(a\right)}\left(x,y\right)=\int_{p}\mathrm{e}^{-ip\left(x-y\right)}\Delta^{\left(a\right)}\left(p\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the Keldysh component, one has 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Calzetta1988"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta^{\mathrm{T}}\left(p\right) & = & \frac{1}{p^{2}-m^{2}+i\epsilon}-2\pi if\left(p\right)\delta\left(p^{2}-m^{2}\right),\\
\Delta^{<}\left(p\right)=\Delta^{>}\left(-p\right) & = & -2\pi i\left[\Theta\left(p^{0}\right)+f\left(p\right)\right]\delta\left(p^{2}-m^{2}\right),\\
\Delta^{\tilde{\mathrm{T}}}\left(p\right) & = & -\frac{1}{p^{2}-m^{2}-i\epsilon}-2\pi if\left(p\right)\delta\left(p^{2}-m^{2}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{<}\left(p\right)=\Delta^{>}\left(-p\right)$
\end_inset

 follows by Hermiticity of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

, and the fact that the same function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 is found on all of the right hand sides is due to the fact that the commutator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 is a c-number, so its expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $-i\left\langle \left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right]\right\rangle =\Delta^{>}\left(x,y\right)-\Delta^{<}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of the state.
 By considering the anticommutator 
\begin_inset Formula $-i\left\{ \hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right\} =\Delta^{>}\left(x,y\right)+\Delta^{<}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 must be real and even.
 Another constraint is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{xy}h^{\star}\left(x\right)i\Delta^{<}\left(x,y\right)h\left(y\right)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all real functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, an equilibrium computation shows that there 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 is just the Bose-Einstein occupation number of the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 naturally has the interpretation of a statistical distribution function
 which can be extended to arbitrary states.
 Thus knowledge of the Green function is equivalent to knowledge of the
 statistical distribution function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other observables of the theory are simply related to the Green functions
 since they are polynomials in the fields and their derivatives.
 For example, in a theory with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 scalar fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

, with an 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry, the conserved 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 currents are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
j_{\mu}^{A}=i\left\langle \phi_{a}T_{ab}^{A}\overleftrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}\phi_{b}\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{A}=-T_{ba}^{A}$
\end_inset

 is a generator of rotations which has been written in a basis of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1,\cdots,N\left(N-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 independent generators and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\overleftrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}g\equiv f\left(\partial_{\mu}g\right)-\left(\partial_{\mu}f\right)g$
\end_inset

.
 This can be written in terms of the Green function as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
j_{\mu}^{A}\left(x\right)=iT_{ab}^{A}\left.\left(\partial_{\mu}^{\left(y\right)}-\partial_{\mu}^{\left(x\right)}\right)\left\langle \phi_{a}\left(x\right)\phi_{b}\left(y\right)\right\rangle \right|_{y\to x}=T_{ab}^{A}\left.\left(\partial_{\mu}^{\left(x\right)}-\partial_{\mu}^{\left(y\right)}\right)\Delta_{ab}^{>}\left(x,y\right)\right|_{y\to x}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly, if the theory has a quartic coupling the energy-momentum tensor
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}=\left\langle \partial_{\mu}\phi_{a}\partial_{\nu}\phi_{a}-\eta_{\mu\nu}\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\rho}\phi_{a}\partial^{\rho}\phi_{a}-\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi_{a}\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}\right)\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\left(4\right)}=\left\langle \mathrm{T}_{C}\left[\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\phi_{c}\phi_{d}\right]\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

